XSS on Wildcard Subdomain

üìñ Description
  This occurs when a subdomain:
  Returns the same response for any path (wildcard behavior)
  Reflects user input (URL path / parameters)
  Does not properly sanitize the input
  This allows attackers to inject and execute JavaScript.

üåç What is a Wildcard Response?
A wildcard subdomain:
  Accepts any random path
  Returns 200 OK
  Shows the same page content

Example:
  https://sub.domain.com/test
  https://sub.domain.com/abc123
  https://sub.domain.com/random

All return the same page.

üéØ Where XSS Happens
  If the application reflects:
  URL path
  Query parameters
  Headers

Without sanitization, attacker can inject:
  "><svg/onload=alert(1)>


If executed ‚Üí Valid XSS

üß≠ Testing Methodology
1Ô∏è‚É£ Find Live Subdomains
  subfinder -d domain.com | httpx
2Ô∏è‚É£ Check Wildcard Behavior
  Visit:
  /random123
  /testxyz
  /anything

If same response ‚Üí wildcard confirmed.
3Ô∏è‚É£ Test Reflection

Try:
  https://sub.domain.com/<payload>
  https://sub.domain.com/?q=<payload>

Check if input appears in response.

4Ô∏è‚É£ Inject XSS Payload
  "><svg/onload=alert(1)>

If popup triggers ‚Üí vulnerability confirmed.

‚ö†Ô∏è Why It‚Äôs Dangerous
Every URL becomes an injection point
Hard to detect with normal crawling
Can affect all users of that subdomain
Useful for chaining (CORS, token theft)
